WEBVTT

00:10.820 --> 00:15.300
The Adventures of Tom Sawyer by Mark Twain.

00:15.900 --> 00:19.160
To my wife, this book is affectionately dedicated.

00:19.980 --> 00:20.540
Preface.

00:21.680 --> 00:26.160
Most of the adventures recorded in this book really occurred. One or two

00:26.160 --> 00:30.880
were experiences of my own, the rest those of boys who were schoolmates

00:30.880 --> 00:36.860
of mine. Huck Finn is drawn from life, Tom Sawyer also, but not from an

00:36.860 --> 00:41.040
individual. He is a combination of the characteristics of three boys

00:41.040 --> 00:45.740
whom I knew, and therefore belongs to the composite order of architecture.

00:46.460 --> 00:50.760
The odds superstitions touched upon were all prevalent among children

00:50.760 --> 00:55.120
and slaves in the West at the period of this story, that is to say thirty

00:55.120 --> 00:59.940
or forty years ago. Although my book is intended mainly for the

00:59.940 --> 01:04.280
entertainment of boys and girls, I hope it will not be shunned by men

01:04.280 --> 01:08.540
and women on that account, for part of my plan has been to try to

01:08.540 --> 01:13.720
pleasantly remind adults of what they once were themselves, and of how

01:13.720 --> 01:18.460
they felt and thought and talked, and what queer enterprises they

01:18.460 --> 01:20.220
sometimes engaged in.

01:20.220 --> 01:24.860
The Author. Hartford. 1876.

01:26.080 --> 01:27.360
CHAPTER I.

01:28.740 --> 01:29.520
No answer.

01:30.160 --> 01:30.740
Tom?

01:31.320 --> 01:32.440
No answer.

01:32.900 --> 01:36.280
What's gone with that boy, I wonder? You, Tom?

01:36.840 --> 01:41.780
No answer. The old lady pulled her spectacles down and looked over them

01:41.780 --> 01:50.200
about the room, then she put them up and looked out under them. She

01:50.200 --> 01:55.200
They were her state-pair, the pride of her heart, and were built for

01:55.200 --> 01:59.540
style, not service. She could have seen through a pair of stove-lids

01:59.540 --> 02:04.320
just as well. She looked perplexed for a moment, and then said, not

02:04.320 --> 02:07.380
fiercely, but still loud enough for the furniture to hear,

02:07.700 --> 02:12.420
"'Well, I lay, if I get hold of you, I'll--" She did not finish, for by

02:12.420 --> 02:16.520
this time she was bending down and punching under the bed with a broom,

02:16.520 --> 02:21.300
and so she needed breath to punctuate the punches with. She resurrected

02:21.300 --> 02:26.600
nothing but the cat. I never see the beat of that boy! She went to the

02:26.600 --> 02:30.400
open door and stood in it, and looked out among the tomato-vines and

02:30.400 --> 02:36.140
jimson-weeds that constituted the garden. No, Tom. So she lifted up her

02:36.140 --> 02:39.300
voice at an angle calculated for distance, and shouted,

02:41.960 --> 02:46.320
"'You, Tom!' There was a slight noise behind her, and she turned just

02:46.320 --> 02:50.560
in time to seize a small boy by the slack of his roundabout, and arrest

02:50.560 --> 02:55.000
his flight. There! I might a thought of that closet. What you been

02:55.000 --> 03:00.380
doing in there? Nothing? Nothing? Look at your hands, and look at your

03:00.380 --> 03:07.080
mouth. What is that truck? I don't know, Aunt. Well, I know. It's jam,

03:07.320 --> 03:11.420
that's what it is. Forty times I've said, if you didn't let that jam

03:11.420 --> 03:14.360
alone, I'll skin you. Hand me that switch."

03:14.360 --> 03:17.640
The switch hovered in the air. The peril was desperate.

03:18.160 --> 03:20.460
"'My! Look behind you, Aunt!'

03:20.460 --> 03:24.200
The old lady whirled round and snatched her skirts out of danger. The

03:24.200 --> 03:27.600
lad fled on the instant, scrambled up the high board-fence and

03:27.600 --> 03:31.960
disappeared over it. His Aunt Polly stood surprised a moment, and then

03:31.960 --> 03:33.460
broke into a gentle laugh.

03:33.940 --> 03:38.440
"'Hang that boy! Can't I never learn anything? Ain't he played me tricks

03:38.440 --> 03:42.680
enough like that for me to be looking out for him by this time? But old

03:42.680 --> 03:46.860
fools is the biggest fools there is. Can't learn an old dog new tricks,

03:46.940 --> 03:51.120
as the saying is. But, my goodness, he never plays them alike two days,

03:51.440 --> 03:55.540
and how is a body to know what's coming? He peers to know just how long

03:55.540 --> 03:59.440
he can torment me before I get my dander up, and he knows if he can

03:59.440 --> 04:03.220
make out to put me off for a minute or make me laugh, it's all down

04:03.220 --> 04:07.120
again and I can't hit him a lick. I ain't doing my duty by that, boy,

04:07.120 --> 04:10.940
and that's the Lord's truth, goodness knows. Spare the rod and smile

04:10.940 --> 04:14.880
at the child, as the Good Book says. I'm a-laying up sin and sufferin'

04:14.940 --> 04:20.100
for us both, I know. He's full of the old scratch but laws of me. He's

04:20.100 --> 04:24.220
my own dead sister's boy, poor thing, and I ain't got the heart to lash

04:24.220 --> 04:28.760
him somehow. Every time I let him off my conscience does hurt me so,

04:29.080 --> 04:33.980
and every time I hit him my old heart most breaks. Well, well, a man

04:33.980 --> 04:40.920
that is born of a woman is a few days and full of trouble, as the

04:41.620 --> 04:46.340
evening. That's south-western for afternoon. And I'll just be

04:46.340 --> 04:51.020
obliged to make him work tomorrow to punish him. It's mighty hard to

04:51.020 --> 04:54.300
make him work Saturdays when all the boys is having holiday, but he

04:54.300 --> 04:58.040
hates work more than he hates anything else, and I've got to do some of

04:58.040 --> 05:01.420
my duty by him, or I'll be the ruination of the child.

05:02.500 --> 05:07.520
Tom did play hooky, and he had a very good time. He got back, home

05:07.520 --> 05:12.360
barely in season to help Jim, the small-colored boy, saw next day's

05:12.360 --> 05:15.900
wood, and split the kindling before supper. At least he was there in

05:15.900 --> 05:19.500
time to tell his adventures to Jim, while Jim did three-fourths of the

05:19.500 --> 05:24.560
work. Tom's younger brother, or rather half-brother, Sid, was already

05:24.560 --> 05:28.140
through with his part of the work, picking up chips, for he was a

05:28.140 --> 05:32.440
quiet boy and had no adventurous, troublesome ways. While Tom was

05:32.440 --> 05:36.140
eating his supper and stealing sugar as opportunity offered, Aunt

05:36.140 --> 05:40.240
Polly asked him questions that were full of guile and very deep, for

05:40.240 --> 05:44.420
she wanted to trap him into damaging revealments. Like many other

05:44.420 --> 05:49.120
simple-hearted souls, it was her pet vanity to believe she was endowed

05:49.120 --> 05:53.340
with a talent for dark and mysterious diplomacy, and she loved to

05:53.340 --> 05:57.380
contemplate her most transparent devices as marvels of low cunning.

05:58.020 --> 05:58.680
Said she,

05:58.680 --> 06:04.760
Tom, it was middling warm in school, wasn't it? Yesen. Powerful warm,

06:04.940 --> 06:10.880
wasn't it? Yesen. Didn't you want to go in a swimmin', Tom? A bit of a

06:10.880 --> 06:14.900
scare shot through Tom, a touch of uncomfortable suspicion. He searched

06:14.900 --> 06:17.960
Aunt Polly's face, but it told him nothing, so he said,

06:18.280 --> 06:20.660
No, well, not very much.

06:21.060 --> 06:24.780
The old lady reached out her hand and felt Tom's shirt, and said,

06:24.780 --> 06:29.200
But you ain't too warm now, though! And it flattered her to reflect that

06:29.200 --> 06:32.800
she had discovered that the shirt was dry without anybody knowing that

06:32.800 --> 06:37.240
that was what she had in her mind. But in spite of her, Tom knew where

06:37.240 --> 06:40.760
the wind lay now, so he forestalled what might be the next move.

06:41.460 --> 06:44.880
Some of us pumped on our heads, minds damp yet, see?

06:45.860 --> 06:48.980
Aunt Polly was vexed to think she had overlooked that bit of

06:48.980 --> 06:52.380
circumstantial evidence and missed a trick. Then she had a new

06:52.380 --> 06:57.400
Tom, you didn't have to undo your shirt collar where I sewed it, to

06:57.400 --> 07:00.160
pump on your head, did you? Unbutton your jacket.

07:00.720 --> 07:04.920
The trouble vanished out of Tom's face. He opened his jacket. His

07:04.920 --> 07:07.060
shirt collar was securely sewed.

07:07.580 --> 07:12.180
Bother! Well, go along with you. I'd made sure you'd played hooky and

07:12.180 --> 07:15.800
been a swimmin', but I forgive you, Tom. I reckon you're a kind of

07:15.800 --> 07:19.760
singed cat, as the saying is. Better in your look. This time.

07:19.760 --> 07:24.520
She was half sorry her sagacity had miscarried, and half glad that Tom

07:24.520 --> 07:28.260
had stumbled into obedient conduct for once. But Sidney said,

07:28.820 --> 07:32.680
Well, now if I didn't think you sewed his collar with white thread,

07:32.800 --> 07:33.660
but it's black.

07:34.360 --> 07:37.160
Why, I did sew it with white. Tom!

07:37.760 --> 07:41.300
But Tom did not wait for the rest. As he went out the door, he said,

07:42.020 --> 07:43.800
City, I'll lick you for that.

07:44.360 --> 07:48.680
In a safe place, Tom examined two large needles, which were thrust

07:48.680 --> 07:52.700
into the lapels of his jacket, and had thread bound about them. One

07:52.700 --> 07:55.760
needle carried white thread, and the other black. He said,

07:56.320 --> 08:00.320
She'd never noticed if it hadn't been for Sid. Con found it. Sometimes

08:00.320 --> 08:04.400
she sews it with white, and sometimes she sews it with black. I wish to

08:04.400 --> 08:08.340
Jiminy she'd stick to one or t'other. I can't keep the run of them. But

08:08.340 --> 08:11.020
I bet I'll learn Sid for that. I'll learn him.

08:11.540 --> 08:15.940
He was not the model boy of the village. He knew the model boy very

08:15.940 --> 08:17.860
well, though, and loathed him.

08:17.860 --> 08:21.520
Within two minutes, or even less, he had forgotten all his troubles.

08:22.140 --> 08:25.620
Not because his troubles were one whit less heavy and bitter to him

08:25.620 --> 08:29.260
than a man's are to a man, but because a new and powerful interest

08:29.260 --> 08:33.600
bore them down, and drove them out of his mind for the time. Just as

08:33.600 --> 08:36.960
men's misfortunes are forgotten in the excitement of new enterprises.

08:37.640 --> 08:41.540
This new interest was a valued novelty in whistling, which he had just

08:41.540 --> 08:45.680
acquired from a negro, and he was suffering to practice it undisturbed.

08:45.680 --> 08:50.320
It consisted in a peculiar bird-like turn, a sort of liquid warble,

08:50.680 --> 08:53.840
produced by touching the tongue to the roof of the mouth at short

08:53.840 --> 08:57.960
intervals in the midst of the music. The reader probably remembers how

08:57.960 --> 09:00.180
to do it, if he has ever been a boy.

09:01.260 --> 09:05.340
Diligence and attention soon gave him the knack of it, and he strode

09:05.340 --> 09:08.540
down the street with his mouth full of harmony and his soul full of

09:08.540 --> 09:12.580
gratitude. He felt much as an astronomer feels who has discovered a

09:12.580 --> 09:16.940
new planet. No doubt, as far as strong, deep, unalloyed pleasure is

09:16.940 --> 09:20.620
concerned, the advantage was with a boy, not the astronomer.

09:21.240 --> 09:26.180
The summer evenings were long. It was not dark yet. Presently Tom

09:26.180 --> 09:30.720
checked his whistle. A stranger was before him, a boy a shade larger

09:30.720 --> 09:35.140
than himself. A newcomer of any age or either sex was an impressive

09:35.140 --> 09:42.560
curiosity in the poor little shabby village of St. Petersburg. This

09:42.560 --> 09:48.280
was simply astounding. His cap was a dainty thing, his close-buttoned

09:48.280 --> 09:52.760
blue cloth round about was new and natty, and so were his pantaloons.

09:53.220 --> 09:58.120
He had shoes on, and it was only Friday. He even wore a necktie, a

09:58.120 --> 10:02.660
bright bit of ribbon. He had acidified air about him that ate into Tom's

10:02.660 --> 10:06.900
vitals. The more Tom stared at the splendid marvel, the higher he

10:06.900 --> 10:11.440
turned up his nose at his finery, and the shabbier and shabbier his own

10:11.440 --> 10:16.220
outfit seemed to him to grow. Neither boy spoke. If one moved, the

10:16.220 --> 10:21.260
other moved, but only sidewise, in a circle. They kept face to face and

10:21.260 --> 10:24.560
eye to eye all the time. Finally Tom said,

10:25.120 --> 10:26.300
I can lick you.

10:26.960 --> 10:28.520
I'd like to see you try it.

10:29.120 --> 10:30.320
Well, I can do it.

10:30.600 --> 10:31.620
No, you can't either.

10:32.180 --> 10:32.960
Yes, I can.

10:33.260 --> 10:34.140
No, you can't.

10:34.140 --> 10:34.760
I can.

10:34.820 --> 10:35.420
You can't.

10:35.420 --> 10:35.960
Can't.

10:36.100 --> 10:36.300
Can't.

10:36.780 --> 10:39.200
An uncomfortable pause. Then Tom said,

10:39.700 --> 10:40.540
What's your name?

10:40.540 --> 10:42.720
It isn't any of your business, maybe.

10:43.520 --> 10:45.820
Well, I'll make it my business.

10:46.300 --> 10:47.700
Well, why don't you?

10:48.140 --> 10:49.740
If you say much, I will.

10:50.900 --> 10:53.480
Much, much, much. There, now.

10:54.060 --> 10:57.380
Oh, you think you're mighty smart, don't you? I could lick you with one

10:57.380 --> 10:59.040
hand tied behind me if I wanted to.

10:59.600 --> 11:02.620
Well, why don't you do it? You say you can do it.

11:02.700 --> 11:04.640
Well, I will, if you fool with me.

11:05.020 --> 11:08.200
Oh, yes, I've seen whole families in the same fix.

11:08.740 --> 11:12.580
Smarty, you think you're some, now, don't you? Oh, what a hat!

11:13.100 --> 11:16.680
You can lump that hat if you don't like it. I dare you to knock it

11:16.680 --> 11:19.460
off. And anybody that'll take a dare will suck eggs.

11:19.940 --> 11:20.800
You're a liar.

11:21.280 --> 11:22.100
You're another.

11:22.560 --> 11:24.720
You're a fighting liar and doesn't take it up.

11:25.120 --> 11:26.300
Ah, take a walk.

11:26.880 --> 11:30.700
Say, if you give me much more of your sass, I'll take and bounce a

11:30.700 --> 11:31.660
rock off in your head.

11:32.140 --> 11:33.540
Oh, of course you will.

11:33.780 --> 11:34.600
Well, I will.

11:35.060 --> 11:36.920
Well, why don't you do it, then?

11:36.920 --> 11:41.420
Why do you keep saying you will for? Why don't you do it? It's

11:41.420 --> 11:42.360
because you're afraid.

11:42.800 --> 11:43.840
I ain't afraid.

11:44.120 --> 11:44.740
You are.

11:45.020 --> 11:45.740
I ain't.

11:45.860 --> 11:46.460
You are.

11:46.900 --> 11:50.580
Another pause, and more eyeing and sidling around each other.

11:50.980 --> 11:53.480
Presently they were shoulder to shoulder, Tom said.

11:53.960 --> 11:57.120
Get away from me. Go away yourself. I won't.

11:57.480 --> 11:58.400
Well, I won't, either.

11:58.700 --> 12:02.760
So they stood, each with a foot placed at an angle as a brace, and

12:02.760 --> 12:06.240
both shoving with might and mane and glowering at each other with

12:06.240 --> 12:10.540
hate. But neither could get an advantage. After struggling till both

12:10.540 --> 12:14.580
were hot and flushed, each relaxed his strain with watchful caution,

12:14.840 --> 12:15.640
and Tom said,

12:16.120 --> 12:20.180
You're a coward and a pup. I'll tell my big brother on you, and he can

12:20.180 --> 12:23.120
thrash you with his little finger, and I'll make him do it, too.

12:23.660 --> 12:27.140
Who do I care for your big brother? I've got a brother that's bigger

12:27.140 --> 12:30.680
than he is, and what's more, he can throw him over that fence, too.

12:31.080 --> 12:32.960
Both brothers were imaginary.

12:32.960 --> 12:36.660
That's a lie! Your saying so doesn't make it so.

12:37.100 --> 12:39.920
Tom drew a line in the dust with his big toe, and said,

12:39.980 --> 12:44.000
I dare you to step over that, and I'll lick you till you can't stand

12:44.000 --> 12:46.980
up. Anybody that'll take a dare will steal sheep.

12:48.040 --> 12:50.240
The new boy stepped over promptly, and said,

12:50.600 --> 12:54.680
Now you said you'd do it. Now let's see you do it. Don't you crowd me

12:54.680 --> 12:56.100
now. You'd better look out.

12:56.700 --> 13:00.480
Well, you said you'd do it. Why don't you do it? Buy jingo for two

13:00.480 --> 13:01.680
pence, I will do it.

13:01.860 --> 13:06.140
The new boy took two broad coppers out of his pocket, and held them out

13:06.140 --> 13:11.420
with derision. Tom struck them to the ground. In an instant both boys

13:11.420 --> 13:15.160
were rolling and tumbling in the dirt, gripped together like cats, and

13:15.160 --> 13:18.260
for the space of a minute they tugged and tore at each other's hair

13:18.260 --> 13:22.080
and clothes, punched and scratched each other's noses, and covered

13:22.080 --> 13:26.300
themselves with dust and glory. Presently the confusion took form,

13:26.440 --> 13:30.180
and through the fog of battle Tom appeared seated astride the new boy,

13:30.180 --> 13:31.940
and pounding him with his fists.

13:32.400 --> 13:36.320
Holler nuff! said he. The boy only struggled to free himself. He was

13:36.320 --> 13:37.900
crying, mainly from rage.

13:38.380 --> 13:42.700
Holler nuff! and the pounding went on. At last the stranger got out of

13:42.700 --> 13:47.140
smothered. Nuff! and Tom let him up, and said, Now that'll learn you.

13:47.340 --> 13:49.420
Better look out who you're fooling with next time.

13:49.980 --> 13:53.400
The new boy went off brushing the dust from his clothes, sobbing,

13:53.500 --> 13:56.340
snuffling, and occasionally looking back and shaking his head and

13:56.340 --> 13:59.240
threatening what he would do to Tom the next time he caught him out,

13:59.240 --> 14:03.040
to which Tom responded with jeers and started off in a high feather,

14:03.400 --> 14:06.720
and as soon as his back was turned the new boy snatched up a stone,

14:07.160 --> 14:10.600
threw it, and hit him between the shoulders, and then turned tail and

14:10.600 --> 14:14.680
ran like an antelope. Tom chased the traitor home, and thus found out

14:14.680 --> 14:18.440
where he lived. He then held a position at the gate for some time,

14:18.820 --> 14:22.760
daring the enemy to come outside, but the enemy only made faces at him

14:22.760 --> 14:26.420
through the window and declined. At last the enemy's mother appeared,

14:26.420 --> 14:31.560
called Tom a bad, vicious, vulgar child, and ordered him away. So he

14:31.560 --> 14:36.320
went away, but he said he allowed to lay for that boy. He got home

14:36.320 --> 14:39.720
pretty late that night, and when he climbed cautiously in at the

14:39.720 --> 14:44.420
window he uncovered an ambuscade in the person of his aunt, and when

14:44.420 --> 14:47.940
she saw the state his clothes were in, her resolution to turn his

14:47.940 --> 14:52.920
Saturday holiday into captivity at hard labor became adamantine in its

14:52.920 --> 14:53.580
firmness.

14:55.060 --> 14:58.180
CHAPTER II THE GLORIOUS WHITE-WASHER

14:59.220 --> 15:04.160
Saturday morning was come, and all the summer world was bright and

15:04.160 --> 15:08.540
fresh and brimming with life. There was a song in every heart, and if

15:08.540 --> 15:13.120
the heart was young the music issued at the lips. There was cheer in

15:13.120 --> 15:18.020
every face, and a spring in every step. The locust trees were in bloom,

15:18.160 --> 15:22.460
and the fragrance of the blossoms filled the air. Cardiff Hill,

15:22.460 --> 15:26.760
beyond the village and above it, was green with vegetation, and it

15:26.760 --> 15:32.000
lay just far enough away to seem a delectable land, dreamy, reposeful

15:32.000 --> 15:36.700
and inviting. Tom appeared on the sidewalk with a bucket of whitewash

15:36.700 --> 15:41.980
and a long-handled brush. He surveyed the fence, and all gladness left

15:41.980 --> 15:47.220
him, and a deep melancholy settled down upon his spirit. Thirty yards

15:47.220 --> 15:52.980
of bored fence nine feet high, life to him seemed hollow, an existence

15:52.980 --> 15:58.080
but a burden. Sighing, he dipped his brush and passed it along the

15:58.080 --> 16:02.760
topmost plank, repeated the operation, did it again, compared the

16:02.760 --> 16:06.560
insignificant whitewash streak with a far-reaching continent of

16:06.560 --> 16:12.180
un-whitewashed fence, and sat down on a tree-box discouraged. Jim came

16:12.180 --> 16:17.220
out at the gate with a tin pail and singing Buffalo Gals. Bringing

16:17.220 --> 16:21.140
water from the town pump had always been hateful work in Tom's eyes

16:21.140 --> 16:25.700
before, but now it did not strike him so. He remembered that there was

16:25.700 --> 16:30.560
company at the pump. White, mulatto, and negro boys and girls were

16:30.560 --> 16:34.380
always there waiting their turns, resting, trading, playthings,

16:34.500 --> 16:38.990
quarreling, fighting, skylarking, and he remembered that although the

16:38.990 --> 16:43.130
pump was only a hundred and fifty yards off, Jim never got back with a

16:43.130 --> 16:47.090
bucket of water under an hour, and even then somebody generally had to

16:47.090 --> 16:49.290
go after him. Tom said,

16:49.750 --> 16:53.610
"'Say, Jim, I'll fetch the water if you'll whitewash some.'

16:53.610 --> 16:55.370
Jim shook his head and said,

16:55.970 --> 17:00.410
"'Can't, Mars Tom. Old Mrs. she told me I got to go and get this water

17:00.410 --> 17:04.510
and stop fooling around with anybody. She say she spec'd Mars Tom

17:04.510 --> 17:08.290
going to ask me to whitewash, and so she told me to go long and tend to

17:08.290 --> 17:13.470
my own business. She loud she'd tend to whitewashing. Oh, never mind

17:13.470 --> 17:16.790
what she said, Jim. That's the way she always talks. Give me the

17:16.790 --> 17:21.090
bucket. I won't be gone only a minute. She won't ever know. Oh, I

17:21.090 --> 17:26.050
dazzle Mars Tom. Old Mrs. she takin' tar to head off in me. Deed she

17:26.670 --> 17:27.170
would.'

17:27.170 --> 17:31.550
"'She never licks anybody, whacks him over the head with her thimble,

17:31.610 --> 17:35.470
and who cares for that, I'd like to know. She talks awful, but talk

17:35.470 --> 17:40.690
hurt. Anyways, it don't if she don't cry. Jim, I'll give you a marvel.

17:41.150 --> 17:43.830
I'll give you a white alley.'

17:43.830 --> 17:45.650
Jim began to wave her.

17:45.910 --> 17:49.810
"'White alley, Jim. And it's a bully-tall.'

17:49.810 --> 17:54.770
"'Mah, that's a mighty gay marvel, I tell you. But Mars Tom, I's

17:54.770 --> 17:58.870
powerful, afraid old Mrs. and besides, if you will, I'll show you my

17:58.870 --> 18:03.750
sore toe.' Jim was only human. This attraction was too much for him. He

18:03.750 --> 18:08.210
put down his pail, took the white alley, and bent over the toe with

18:08.210 --> 18:11.750
absorbing interest while the bandage was being unwound. In another

18:11.750 --> 18:15.330
moment he was flying down the street with his pail and a tingling rear.

18:15.770 --> 18:19.890
Tom was whitewashing with vigour, and Aunt Polly was retiring from the

18:19.890 --> 18:24.910
field with a slipper in her hand and triumph in her eye. But Tom's

18:24.910 --> 18:29.070
energy did not last. He began to think of the fun he had planned for

18:29.070 --> 18:34.110
his day, and his sorrows multiplied. Soon the free boys would come

18:34.110 --> 18:37.910
tripping along on all sorts of delicious expeditions, and they would

18:37.910 --> 18:41.270
make a world of fun of him for having to work. The very thought of it

18:41.270 --> 18:46.130
burnt him like fire. He got out his worldly wealth and examined it—bits

18:46.130 --> 18:51.870
of toys, marbles, and trash—enough to buy an exchange of work, maybe,

18:52.150 --> 18:56.750
but not half enough to buy so much as half an hour of pure freedom. So

18:56.750 --> 19:00.750
he returned his straightened means to his pocket and gave up the idea of

19:00.750 --> 19:05.130
trying to buy the boys. At this dark and hopeless moment an inspiration

19:05.130 --> 19:10.090
burst upon him—nothing less than a great magnificent inspiration. He

19:10.090 --> 19:14.770
took up his brush and went tranquilly to work. Ben Rogers hove in sight

19:14.770 --> 19:18.970
presently—the very boy of all boys, whose ridicule he had been

19:18.970 --> 19:23.910
dreading. Ben's gait was the hop, skip, and jump, proof enough that his

19:23.910 --> 19:28.630
heart was light and his anticipations high. He was eating an apple, and

19:28.630 --> 19:33.310
giving a long, melodious whoop at intervals, followed by a deep-toned

19:33.310 --> 19:39.870
ding-dong-dong, ding-dong-dong, for he was personating a steamboat. As he

19:39.870 --> 19:43.930
drew near he slackened speed, took the middle of the road, leaned far

19:43.930 --> 19:48.490
over to starboard, and rounded to, ponderously and with laborious pomp

19:48.490 --> 19:52.890
and circumstance, for he was personating the Big Missouri, and considered

19:52.890 --> 19:57.690
himself to be drawing nine feet of water. He was boat and captain and

19:57.690 --> 20:01.750
engine-bells combined, so he had to imagine himself standing on his own

20:01.750 --> 20:04.190
hurricane deck giving the orders and executing them.

20:04.530 --> 20:09.210
Stop her, sir! Ding-a-ling-a-ling! The headway ran almost out, and he

20:09.210 --> 20:13.670
drew up slowly towards the sidewalk. Ship up to back! Ding-a-ling-a-ling!

20:14.070 --> 20:18.270
His arms straightened and stiffened down his sides. Set her back on the

20:18.270 --> 20:23.330
starboard! Ding-a-ling-a-ling! Chow! Chow! Chow! Chow! Chow! His right

20:23.330 --> 20:27.370
hand, meantime, described stately circles, for it was representing a 40

20:27.370 --> 20:32.150
foot wheel. Let her go back on the starboard! Ding-a-ling-a-ling! Chow!

20:32.290 --> 20:37.110
Chow! Chow! The left hand began to describe circles. Stop the starboard!

20:37.290 --> 20:41.730
Ding-a-ling-a-ling! Stop the starboard! Come ahead on the starboard!

20:42.070 --> 20:47.650
Stop her! Let her outside! Turn her over slow! Ding-a-ling! Chow! Chow!

20:47.650 --> 20:52.270
Get out that headline! Lively, now! Come! Come out of there with your

20:52.270 --> 20:55.870
spring line! What are you about there? Take up a turn in that stump

20:55.870 --> 21:00.550
with the bright of it! Stand by that stage! Now let her go! Done with

21:00.550 --> 21:05.530
the engine, sir! Ding-a-ling-a-ling! Chit! Chit! Chit! Chit!

21:05.690 --> 21:10.390
Trying the gauge-cocks, Tom went on whitewashing, paid no attention to

21:10.390 --> 21:13.130
the steamboat. Ben stared a moment and then said,

21:13.130 --> 21:16.450
Hi-ee! You're up a stump, ain't you?

21:16.830 --> 21:21.450
No answer. Tom surveyed his last touch with the eye of an artist, then

21:21.450 --> 21:24.710
he gave his brush another gentle sweep and surveyed the result as

21:24.710 --> 21:29.750
before. Ben ranged up alongside of him. Tom's mouth watered for the

21:29.750 --> 21:32.310
apple, but he stuck to his work. Ben said,

21:32.750 --> 21:35.090
Hello, old chap! You got to work, eh?

21:35.810 --> 21:37.630
Tom wheeled suddenly and said,

21:37.630 --> 21:42.990
Why, it's you, Ben. I weren't noticing. Say, I'm going in a swimming.

21:43.210 --> 21:47.090
I am. Don't you wish you could? But of course you'd rather work,

21:47.190 --> 21:50.610
wouldn't you? Of course you would. Tom contemplated the boy a bit and

21:50.610 --> 21:50.970
said,

21:51.530 --> 21:53.190
What do you call work?

21:53.730 --> 21:57.470
Why, ain't that work? Tom resumed his whitewashing and answered

21:57.470 --> 21:58.010
carelessly,

21:58.710 --> 22:04.010
Well, maybe it is and maybe it ain't. All I know is it suits Tom Sawyer.

22:04.570 --> 22:08.790
Oh, come, now, you don't mean to let on that you like that.

22:09.330 --> 22:10.830
The brush continued to move.

22:11.130 --> 22:15.630
Like it? Well, I don't see why I oughtn't to like it. Does a boy get a

22:15.630 --> 22:17.310
chance to whitewash a fence every day?

22:17.970 --> 22:21.850
That put the thing in a new light. Ben stopped nibbling his apple.

22:22.370 --> 22:26.990
Tom swept his brush daintily, back and forth, stepped back to note the

22:26.990 --> 22:31.810
effect, added a touch here and there, criticized the effect again. Ben,

22:31.810 --> 22:34.950
watching every move and getting more and more interested, more and

22:34.950 --> 22:36.890
more absorbed. Presently he said,

22:37.410 --> 22:40.510
Say, Tom, let me whitewash a little.

22:41.090 --> 22:44.870
Tom considered, was about to consent, but he altered his mind.

22:45.210 --> 22:49.830
No, no, I reckon it wouldn't hardly do, Ben. You see Aunt Polly's awful

22:49.830 --> 22:53.430
particular about this fence, right here on the street, you know. But if

22:53.430 --> 22:56.950
it was the back fence I wouldn't mind and she wouldn't. Yes, she's

22:56.950 --> 23:01.490
awful particular about this fence. It's got to be done very careful. I

23:01.490 --> 23:05.210
reckon there ain't one boy in a thousand—maybe two thousand—that

23:05.210 --> 23:07.030
can do it the way it's got to be done.

23:07.610 --> 23:13.290
No, is that so? Oh, come now, let me just try. Only just a little. I'd

23:13.290 --> 23:14.830
let you if you was me, Tom.

23:15.530 --> 23:18.690
Ben, I'd like to. Honest, Injun. But Aunt Polly—

23:19.290 --> 23:24.250
Well, Jim wanted to do it, but she wouldn't let him. Sid wanted to do

23:24.250 --> 23:28.990
it, and she wouldn't let Sid. Now, don't you see how I'm fixed? If you

23:28.990 --> 23:32.370
was to tackle this fence and anything was to happen to it—aw, shucks,

23:32.370 --> 23:37.570
I'll be just as careful. Now let me try. Say, I'll give you the core of

23:37.570 --> 23:37.990
my apple.

23:38.850 --> 23:44.710
Well, here. No, no, Ben, now don't. I'm afeard. I'll give you all of

23:44.710 --> 23:44.850
it.

23:45.150 --> 23:49.430
Tom gave up the brush with reluctance in his face, but alacrity in his

23:49.430 --> 23:53.550
heart, and while the late steamer Big Missouri worked and sweated in

23:53.550 --> 23:57.630
the sun, the retired artist sat on a barrel in the shade close by,

23:57.630 --> 24:02.130
dangled his legs, munched his apple, and planned the slaughter of more

24:02.130 --> 24:06.650
innocence. There was no lack of material. Boys happened along every

24:06.650 --> 24:11.530
little while. They came to jeer, but remained to whitewash. By the time

24:11.530 --> 24:15.530
Ben was fagged out, Tom had traded the next chance to Billy Fisher for

24:15.530 --> 24:20.170
a kite in good repair. And when he played out, Johnny Miller bought in

24:20.170 --> 24:24.910
for a dead rat on a string to swing it with, and so on and so on hour

24:24.910 --> 24:29.170
after hour. And when the middle of the afternoon came, from being a

24:29.170 --> 24:33.190
poor poverty-stricken boy in the morning, Tom was literally rolling in

24:33.190 --> 24:37.970
wealth. He had beside the things before mentioned twelve marbles, part

24:37.970 --> 24:42.530
of a Jew's harp, a piece of blue bottle-glass to look through, a spool

24:42.530 --> 24:47.390
cannon, a key that wouldn't unlock anything, a fragment of chalk, a

24:47.390 --> 24:53.130
glass stopper of a decanter, a tin soldier, a couple of tadpoles, six

24:53.130 --> 24:58.830
firecrackers, a kitten with only one eye, a brass doorknob, a dog collar

24:58.830 --> 25:03.890
but no dog, the handle of a knife, four pieces of orange peel, and a

25:03.890 --> 25:09.750
dilapidated old window-sash. He had had a nice, good, idle time all the

25:09.750 --> 25:13.410
while, plenty of company, and the fence had had three coats of

25:13.410 --> 25:17.250
whitewash on it. If he hadn't run out of whitewash, he would have

25:17.250 --> 25:18.850
bankrupted every boy in the village.

25:19.530 --> 25:24.130
Tom said to himself that it was not such a hollow world after all. He

25:24.130 --> 25:28.250
had discovered a great law of human action without knowing it, namely,

25:28.290 --> 25:32.730
that in order to make a man or boy covet a thing, it is only necessary

25:32.730 --> 25:37.350
to make the thing difficult to attain. If he had been a great and wise

25:37.350 --> 25:40.790
philosopher, like the writer of this book, he would now have

25:40.790 --> 25:45.710
comprehended that work consists of whatever a body is obliged to do,

25:45.710 --> 25:51.250
and that play consists of whatever a body is not obliged to do. And

25:51.250 --> 25:55.030
this would help him to understand why constructing artificial flowers

25:55.030 --> 26:00.450
or performing on a treadmill is work, while rolling tenpins or climbing

26:00.450 --> 26:05.290
Mont Blanc is only amusement. There are wealthy gentlemen in England

26:05.290 --> 26:09.810
who drive four-horse passenger coaches twenty or thirty miles on a

26:09.810 --> 26:13.650
daily line in the summer because the privilege costs them considerable

26:13.650 --> 26:18.190
money. But if they were offered wages for the service, that would turn

26:18.190 --> 26:23.290
it into work, and then they would resign. The boy mused a while over

26:23.290 --> 26:26.250
the substantial change which had taken place in his worldly

26:26.250 --> 26:30.730
circumstances, and then wended toward headquarters to report.

